snippet.textDisplay: Veganism is the most frustrating form of ignorance. MEAT IS NOT BAD FOR YOU. Red meat is more harmful BECAUSE it is higher in saturated fat content. If you eat lean proteins like chicken and fish you’re already significantly better off. Meat contains PLENTY of essential nutrients that you CANNOT get from a plant only diet. You should eat a balanced diet of meats, vegetables, and fruits. ADDITIONALLY, red meat IS NOT harmful but should be eaten in moderation. DIET is based on exercise out put. If you load your body with high sugars and do not use them YOU WILL gain weight in the FORM OF FAT by the lack of expelling the sugar from your body, this will also lead to congestive heart failure because you have increased sugar and saturated fat. Your body converts all unused nutrients to stored fat via a process called GLUCONEOGENESIS. Being vegan is not a magic cure. Eating real food is a cure. Meat is not bad for your body. If you want to be healthy and actually care about your body stop eating ice cream, cookies, pop tarts, candy, pizza, beer, mayonnaise, and soy based foods (which increase estrogen levels and affect hormones in the body). It is so frustrating as someone who has gotten a college degree in science to watch people be mislead by a cultish movement. I only respect being vegan for people who care about animal cruelty, other than that, being a vegan for health benefits is essentially pointless and more damaging because most people who become vegan lack so many nutrients only attainable by meats and have to depend on NON REGULATED supplements.

snippet.textDisplay: I really enjoy watching Yes Theory but I believe this "experiment" can be misleading and lead people to be misinformed. However, although this video is from personal experience, it is important to say that this diet would not lead to the same results on everyone. There are many factors that even before the experiment happened could have already affected the results such as the Volunteerism effect, and the Hawthorne effect, in which his willingness to follow the diet and the special attention he is devoting to the diet have an effect on the results. Plus the fact that he is actually watching what he is eating might actually be the reason for the change and not the actual food included in the diet. I believe it would be best to compare a vegetarian diet in which he watches what he eats to an omnivore diet in which he also watches what he eats. Although the vegetarian diet has been researched and found many benefits, there are many drawbacks. And this can even discourage people to even try the diet since most people are "all or nothing". This channel is extremely popular and can serve as a source of information for many people. Thanks for the great content!
